Here we must notice the double meaning of the word secular, (1) as applied to lay- men living in the world, (ii) as ap- plied to all, whether lay or cleric, living out- side the cloister.

It must have been owing to the irregular and worldly life of some oi the clergy that these were called secular in opposition to those whose holi- ness won the name of religz'ous or regular.
